21:08.411 --> 21:09.112
One more point here. I was talking with Peter Boyce 
about the state of planetary astronomy in the 20s

21:09.132 --> 21:20.307
and 30s when not only was it held in low repute by a 
other astronomers, but also results were few and

21:20.523 --> 21:37.283
far between, and probably a lot of that was due to 
the fact that there was an instrumentation

21:20.523 --> 21:37.283
barrier, both as to wavelength and stability for 
photometry and wavelength for detectors for

21:20.523 --> 21:37.283
spectroscopy, and so you were just about to say 
something about that. I was saying it's

21:37.870 --> 21:49.190
absolutely true that the kind of instrumentation 
that you use for stellar photometry, by and large,

21:37.870 --> 21:49.190
is not very useful for planetary astronomy. 
Telescopes, for instance, if you're trying to

21:49.650 --> 21:59.608
track a fast-moving asteroid, are hard to point 
when you're doing photometry on. So people didn't

21:59.628 --> 22:02.713
do photometry on asteroids. The visible light 
photometry doesn't tell you a great deal about the

22:03.065 --> 22:08.471
asteroids. You have to get into the infrared to 
really pick out the different asteroid families.

22:13.257 --> 22:16.220
And the infrared detectors weren't there. And 
they were not very much encouraged. Their use was

22:20.164 --> 22:28.754
not very encouraged in astrophysics, at least in 
my experience. It was quite unusual. to have

22:30.858 --> 22:34.682
somebody like Bill Sinton actually working at two 
microns. And early on, I know when I went to

22:35.202 --> 22:58.907
graduate school at Michigan, we were

22:35.202 --> 22:58.907
concentrated so heavily on the visible and near 
ultraviolet and near infrared, because that's

22:35.202 --> 22:58.907
where all the spectrum lines of interest were in 
the stellar atmospheres at that temperature

22:35.202 --> 22:58.907
range that We just didn't really pay much 
attention to the infrared at all, and yet that's

22:59.258 --> 23:11.375
exactly the kind of area you need to be in when 
you're doing planetary astronomy. High Spinrat

23:11.475 --> 23:18.285
and I used to and still do refer to H-alpha, which of 
course is in the red region of the spectrum, as the

23:11.475 --> 23:18.285
Mount Wilson infrared. Oh, yeah. No, that's it. I 
mean, High's work on water vapor in... the late

23:27.558 --> 23:34.808
type stars was almost pioneering work in those 
days. Very, very important kind of thing to be

23:36.209 --> 23:39.474
done. And it just, a lot of people didn't do that. I 
mean, they were just happy with the information

23:43.038 --> 23:49.867
they were getting, the physics that they knew in 
the visible. And I think that probably had... That

23:52.077 --> 23:58.488
was why planetary astronomers couldn't do 
anything except take pictures and look at them.

23:59.249 --> 24:06.421
There just wasn't the ability to measure small 
parts of the planetary disk photoelectrically.

